Taxes and Town/Gown Relations in Evanston

fields.text: test summary

Relations between Evanston and Northwestern are notoriously strained, whether because of student partying incidents over Halloween or because of the more festering issue: property taxes. Whenever the Evanston city clerk announces the new property tax rate for the coming year, tensions can be expected to flare up between the community and university. But tempers may cool down this year after the clerk’s announcement Monday that the new rate will drop to 6.136 from 6.485 the previous year, a 5 percent decline.

Some residents blame Northwestern for adding to their tax burden, since the university’s charter exempts its 250 acres of lakefront property from property tax base. Many also complain that the university doesn’t pay its fair share for city services. But Northwestern cites the economic activity its students bring to local businesses as a counterweight to these claims, as well as to property sales tax from when the university sells property back to private owners.

Relations between Evanston and Northwestern University are defined by the university's tax-exempt status, the cultural and economic contributions the university makes and the behavior of Northwestern students in Evanston.

  • Northwestern is exempt from paying property taxes on its 250 acres of prime lakefront property. Some residents, the Chicago Tribune's reported,  see this as placing an unfair burden on other taxpayers. But tempers may cool down this year after the clerk’s announcement Monday that the new property tax rate will drop to 6.136 from 6.485 the previous year, a 5 percent decline.
  • Northwestern employs Evanstonians, and students and staff spend money in town.
  • Many Northwestern cultural events are open to the public at large. The university maintains an online calendar of events.
  • Northwestern students have often been cited for lewd and inconsiderate behavior. Most recently, Evanston residents complained about noise and public urination by partying students, and the university felt the need to caution its students not to dress in blackface on Halloween.

fields.text: Northwestern University generates more than $145 million in revenues for the Evanston economy on a yearly basis, according to the first comprehensive economic impact study of its kind.

Northwestern University generates more than $145 million in revenues for the Evanston economy on a yearly basis, according to the first comprehensive economic impact study of its kind.

The study examined revenues paid directly to the city by Northwestern and University-generated purchases at businesses.

The study by Bay Area Economics, a national urban economics consulting firm, analyzed information from the 2004 fiscal years of the University and City of Evanston.
fields.user_comments: This article talks about a study done in 2006 on the economic activity Northwestern generates in Evanston.

fields.text: Marking the beginning of Dr. Schapiro’s tenure at the University, Northwestern donated $550,000 for the City to purchase a new fire engine.

With over 25 campus organizations dedicated to volunteering and community involvement, Northwestern is a huge volunteer force for Evanston and the greater Chicago area.  Natalie Furlett, student community service coordinator at the Center for Student Involvement at Northwestern estimates that, between students who engage in large service organizations like Northwestern Community Development Corps and Dance Marathon, those who work with smaller, specialized organizations like Special Olympics and those who engage with community service through their Greek affiliations, upwards of 75 percent of Northwestern students engage in community service. Much of that service is performed in Evanston.
fields.user_comments: Not the University directly, but lots of NU students are involved in community service activities.

fields.text: The many partnerships between the City of Evanston and Northwestern University formed the basis of the City Council’s discussion on the Council’s "Northwestern University" goal on Nov. 23. The goal, City Manager Wally Bobkiewicz reminded Council members, was one with "no particular parameters."

A statute of Illinois passed in 1865 declares that all the property of the Northwestern University shall be for ever free from taxation. As construed by the assessors and by the supreme court of the state, a statute of 1872 conforming taxation to the new constitution of 1870 limited this exemption to land and other property in immediate use by the institution.
fields.user_comments: If it's about taxes, the issue goes back all the way to 1965, when the state passed the university's charter exempting it from taxes forever.
